**MITRE ATT&CK Technique – T0872 – “Exfiltration Over Symmetric Encrypted Non‑C2 Channel”**  
*(Mobile/IoT ATT&CK matrix – also applicable to cloud‑native workloads that use custom encrypted tunnels for data‑out)*  

| Aspect | Cloud‑relevant interpretation |
|--------|------------------------------|
| **Goal of the adversary** | Move data from a compromised workload to an external location using a private, symmetric‑key encrypted channel that is *not* a known C2 protocol. Because the traffic is encrypted end‑to‑end, traditional network‑based detection (e.g., DPI) is ineffective. |
| **Typical vectors** | • Custom TLS/DTLS tunnels built into an application binary.<br>• Use of VPN‑like tunnels (e.g., WireGuard, OpenVPN) spun up by a compromised container or EC2 instance.<br>• Cloud‑native services that expose encrypted “upload” APIs (e.g., S3 PUT with client‑side encryption) that the attacker abuses. |
| **Why it is dangerous in the cloud** | Cloud environments often trust encrypted traffic by default (e.g., VPC traffic is allowed if it terminates on a known port). If the encryption keys are under the attacker’s control, data can leave the environment without generating any observable “unusual” API calls. |

