## 2. Secure‑Configuration Controls (AWS‑Specific)

| Control | Why it matters | Secure‑by‑design implementation |
|---------|----------------|---------------------------------|
| **IAM Least‑Privilege** | Over‑privileged roles enable lateral movement. | • Use **managed policies** that enumerate exact actions.<br>• Avoid `*` in `Action` or `Resource`.<br>• Add **condition keys** (`aws:RequestedRegion`, `aws:MultiFactorAuthPresent`). |
| **S3 Bucket Hardening** | Public buckets leak data. | • Enforce **BlockPublicAccess**.<br>• Require **Server‑Side Encryption** (SSE‑KMS).<br>• Enable **Object Lock** for immutable logs. |
| **KMS Key Policies** | Unrestricted key use leads to data exfiltration. | • Scope key usage to specific IAM principals.<br>• Enforce **CMK rotation** and **audit** via CloudTrail. |
| **VPC Flow Logs & Security Groups** | Open ports expose services. | • Default‑deny inbound; allow only required ports.<br>• Use **Security Group References** instead of CIDR where possible.<br>• Enable **VPC Flow Logs** to CloudWatch Logs. |
| **AWS Config Rules** | Detect drift from baseline. | • `s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited`, `ec2-instance-no-public-ip`, `iam-user-mfa-enabled`, etc.<br>• Custom Lambda‑backed rules for organization‑specific checks. |
| **Patch Management** | Unpatched OS/firmware are exploitable. | • Use **AWS Systems Manager Patch Manager** with approved baselines.<br>• Enforce **maintenance windows** and **auto‑approval** for critical CVEs. |
| **Logging & Monitoring** | Lack of visibility hides attacks. | • Enable **CloudTrail** (multi‑region, log file integrity).<br>• Forward logs to **Amazon OpenSearch** or **Splunk** for SIEM correlation.<br>• Activate **GuardDuty** and **Security Hub**. |
| **MFA & Credential Hygiene** | Stolen credentials are a primary vector. | • Enforce **MFA** for all IAM users and privileged roles.<br>• Rotate **access keys** every 90 days; disable unused keys. |
| **Encryption‑in‑Transit** | Man‑in‑the‑middle attacks. | • Enforce **TLS 1.2+** on ALBs, API Gateways, RDS, etc.<br>• Use **AWS Certificate Manager** for managed certs. |

