## 1️⃣ Threat‑Model‑Driven Remediation Overview  

| Phase | Objective | Cloud‑Native Controls & Secure‑by‑Design Practices |
|-------|-----------|------------------------------------------------------|
| **Detect** | Identify encrypted‑exfil traffic **before** it leaves the environment. | • Enable **VPC Flow Logs**, **AWS Network Firewall** with TLS‑inspection (or a proxy that terminates TLS). <br>• Deploy **Amazon GuardDuty** + **ThreatIntel** feeds that flag outbound connections to high‑risk domains or IP ranges. <br>• Turn on **S3 Access Analyzer** and **CloudTrail Data Events** for any bucket used by the app. |
| **Prevent** | Stop the adversary from being able to write data to an uncontrolled egress point. | • Enforce **least‑privilege IAM**: only the exact S3 bucket / API endpoint required for the app gets `s3:PutObject` permission. <br>• Use **AWS CDK** to create **VPC endpoint policies** that restrict traffic to approved services (e.g., only `com.amazonaws.<region>.s3`). <br>• Apply **Egress‑only security groups** and **Network ACLs** that block outbound to the public Internet except via a **managed egress proxy**. |
| **Contain** | Quarantine compromised workloads quickly. | • Tag resources with a **security‑incident** tag; use **AWS Config Rules** to auto‑remediate (e.g., detach overly permissive policies). <br>• Leverage **AWS Systems Manager Session Manager** for controlled access, disabling SSH/ADB ports. |
| **Eradicate** | Remove the attacker’s encryption keys and any persisted malicious binaries. | • Rotate all **KMS** keys used by the app; enforce **automatic key rotation**. <br>• Run **Amazon Inspector** scans on the container / mobile‑backend AMI to locate unknown binaries. |
| **Recover** | Re‑establish a trusted state and improve future detection. | • Re‑enable **CloudWatch Alarms** on anomalous egress volume (e.g., > 10 MiB per minute). <br>• Store a **baseline of normal outbound traffic** in **Amazon Athena** for future anomaly detection. |

