## Mitigation M0804 – Privileged Access Management (PAM)  
**Goal:** Restrict, monitor, and control the use of privileged credentials and capabilities so that an adversary who obtains a privileged token cannot move laterally, exfiltrate data, or persist in the environment.

Below is a **cloud‑native remediation guide** (focused on AWS, but the principles apply to any CSP) that follows the six safety constraints you listed:

| **Area** | **Secure‑by‑design actions** | **Why it matters** | **Telemetry / verification** |
|----------|------------------------------|--------------------|------------------------------|
| **Identity & Access** | • Enforce **least‑privilege** IAM policies (no `*` actions, no `*` resources). <br>• Use **IAM roles** instead of long‑lived access keys. <br>• Require **MFA** for any privileged IAM user or role. <br>• Adopt **Just‑In‑Time (JIT) / temporary elevation** (AWS SSO, IAM Roles Anywhere, or AWS Privilege‑Escalation Guardrails). | Reduces the attack surface; a compromised credential only has the permissions needed for the current task. | CloudTrail event `AssumeRole`, `ConsoleLogin` with `mfaAuthenticated:true`. GuardDuty finding **PrivilegeEscalation**. |
| **Network & Compute** | • Deploy **Privileged Access Workstations (PAWs)** – isolated, hardened EC2 instances that are the only hosts allowed to run privileged actions. <br>• Enforce **VPC‑endpoint‑only** access to IAM, STS, and other control‑plane services from PAWs. | Guarantees that privileged commands originate from a trusted, monitored environment. | VPC Flow Logs showing traffic only from PAW CIDR to `*.amazonaws.com`. |
| **Session Management** | • Enable **AWS Session Manager** with **SSM Document** that forces MFA and logs every command. <br>• Set **maximum session duration** (e.g., 1 h) and **idle timeout** (e.g., 15 min). | Provides auditable, revocable sessions and prevents “forgotten” privileged shells. | SSM Session Manager logs in CloudWatch Logs; CloudTrail `StartSession`/`TerminateSession`. |
| **Credential Hygiene** | • Rotate **access keys** automatically (e.g., via AWS Secrets Manager rotation). <br>• Disable or delete **unused IAM users** (≥ 90 days inactivity). <br>• Enforce **password policy** (minimum length ≥ 14, complexity, password reuse ≤ 5). | Limits the window of opportunity for credential theft. | IAM Credential Report, Config rule `iam-user-unused-credentials-check`. |
| **Monitoring & Alerting** | • Turn on **AWS Config** with managed rules: <br> `iam-user-no-policies-check`, `iam-role-no-inline-policy-check`, `iam-policy-no-statements-with-wildcard-action`. <br>• Enable **GuardDuty** and **Security Hub** for privileged‑access findings. <br>• Deploy **CloudWatch Alarms** on anomalous `AssumeRole` patterns (e.g., role assumed from new IP, from a region not normally used). | Early detection of abuse of privileged accounts. | Config compliance dashboard, GuardDuty findings `PrivilegeEscalation:EC2/NetworkPortUnusual`, Security Hub insights. |
| **Audit & Forensics** | • Centralise **CloudTrail** logs in an immutable S3 bucket with **Object Lock** (WORM). <br>• Enable **AWS CloudTrail Insights** to surface spikes in API activity. <br>• Retain logs ≥ 90 days (or per regulatory requirement). | Guarantees an immutable evidence trail for investigations. | S3 bucket versioning + Object Lock status; CloudTrail `EventTime` correlation. |

