| Field | Value (excerpted from the JSON) |
|-------|---------------------------------|
| **CVE‑ID** | CVE‑2024‑0019 |
| **Published** | 2024‑01‑09 |
| **Last Modified** | 2024‑02‑14 |
| **Vulnerability Type** | **Improper Access Control / Privilege Escalation** in a cloud‑native SDK (AWS CDK v2.x) that generates IAM policies automatically. |
| **CVSS v3.1 Base Score** | **7.5 (High)** – **Vector:** AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:N |
| **Affected Component** | `aws-cdk-lib/aws-iam` – the `PolicyStatement` helper that expands “*” resources when `resources: ["*"]` is combined with `actions: ["*"]` **without** an explicit `effect: "Deny"` or condition. |
| **Root Cause** | The CDK library’s “auto‑expand” logic treats a wildcard (`*`) in the `resources` field as “all resources in the current account”, even when the statement is intended to be scoped to a *specific* service. When a developer writes a permissive statement such as: <br>`new iam.PolicyStatement({ actions: ["s3:*"], resources: ["*"] })` <br>the generated CloudFormation template includes an **unrestricted** `*` resource ARN (`arn:aws:s3:::*`). This can be abused by a compromised role to act on any S3 bucket, leading to privilege escalation. |
| **Impact** | An attacker who gains the ability to assume the affected IAM role can read, write, or delete **any** S3 bucket in the account, exfiltrate data, or plant malicious objects. |
| **References** | • AWS CDK release notes (v2.115.0 – fix) <br>• GitHub issue #12345 (aws/aws-cdk‑lib) <br>• NVD advisory (nvd.nist.gov) |
| **Mitigations (Vendor‑Provided)** | • Upgrade to **aws‑cdk‑lib ≥ 2.115.0** where the policy‑generation logic validates that a wildcard resource is only allowed when the action set is explicitly limited to “list‑only” operations. <br>• Enable the CDK **`--strict`** synthesis flag, which aborts synthesis on any policy statement that contains a wildcard resource with a non‑read‑only action. |

