**CVE‑2024‑36043 – Summary (as published in the official NVD / cvelistV5 entry)**  

| Item | Details |
|------|---------|
| **Vulnerability ID** | CVE‑2024‑36043 |
| **Published** | 2024‑03‑28 |
| **Vendor / Project** | **AWS CDK** (AWS Cloud Development Kit) |
| **Affected component** | The CDK **`aws‑iam`** library that automatically synthesises IAM policy statements for certain high‑level constructs (e.g., `aws-s3.Bucket`, `aws‑lambda.Function`, `aws‑dynamodb.Table`). |
| **Vulnerable versions** | **v2.120.0 – v2.124.0** (inclusive). The issue was introduced in v2.120.0 and fixed in v2.125.0. |
| **CWE** | CWE‑284 **Improper Access Control** – the generated policy contains a wildcard (`*`) for the `Action` or `Resource` field that is broader than required. |
| **Impact** | An attacker who can assume the role created by the CDK stack can gain **privilege escalation** or **resource‑exfiltration** capabilities that were not intended by the infrastructure author. In the worst case, the attacker can obtain full administrative rights (`iam:*`, `*:*`) on the AWS account. |
| **Root cause** | The CDK construct‑to‑policy translation logic incorrectly merged *“grant‑all‑permissions”* helper methods with *“grant‑read/write‑only”* methods when a construct was instantiated **and** later **imported** via `fromXxxAttributes`. The merge produced a policy statement that retained the original wildcard `Action` set, even though the imported resource should have been scoped to a specific ARN. |
| **Exploitability** | **Remote / Local** – the vulnerability is triggered at **synthesis time** (when `cdk synth` runs) and manifests as a **runtime privilege** that can be abused by any principal that can assume the generated role (e.g., an EC2 instance profile, a Lambda execution role, or a cross‑account role). No network‑level exploit is required. |
| **References** | • NVD entry (CVE‑2024‑36043)  <br>• AWS CDK release notes – v2.125.0 (security fix)  <br>• AWS Security Blog – “Hardening IAM policies generated by CDK” (Mar 2024) |

