## 2. Root‑Cause Remediation Checklist  

| Category | Action | Why it mitigates T0817 |
|----------|--------|------------------------|
| **Patch Management** | • Enable **Amazon Inspector** (or a CI/CD integrated scanner) on all AMIs, container images, and managed service versions.<br>• Apply vendor patches within the defined **Mean Time To Patch (MTTP)** window (e.g., 7 days for critical CVEs). | Removes the underlying software flaw that the attacker would exploit. |
| **Least‑Privilege IAM** | • Audit all IAM policies for **privilege‑escalation permissions** (`iam:PassRole`, `sts:AssumeRole`, `iam:CreatePolicyVersion`).<br>• Replace broad wildcards (`*`) with explicit actions and resource ARNs.<br>• Use **IAM Access Analyzer** to surface over‑privileged roles. | Prevents an attacker who compromises a low‑privilege identity from “passing” a higher‑privilege role. |
| **Service Control Policies (SCPs)** | • In an AWS Organization, attach an SCP that denies `iam:PassRole` and `sts:AssumeRole` unless the principal is explicitly allowed.<br>• Example SCP (see code snippet below). | Enforces a hard boundary that cannot be overridden by compromised child accounts. |
| **Metadata Service Hardening** | • Enforce **IMDSv2** (token‑based) on all EC2 instances.<br>• Disable `http://169.254.169.254` access for containers that do not need it. | Stops attackers from stealing temporary credentials from compromised workloads. |
| **Network Segmentation** | • Use **VPC security groups** and **Network ACLs** to isolate management APIs (e.g., RDS admin endpoints) from untrusted subnets.<br>• Deploy **AWS PrivateLink** for internal service calls. | Reduces the attack surface for remote exploitation. |
| **Runtime Protection** | • Enable **AWS Lambda Runtime Protection** (e.g., AWS CodeGuru Security) and **EKS Guard** for container runtime anomalies.<br>• Deploy **AWS Web Application Firewall (WAF)** with managed rule groups that block known exploit payloads. | Detects and blocks exploitation attempts that bypass static controls. |
| **Credential Hygiene** | • Enforce **MFA** for all privileged IAM users.<br>• Rotate access keys automatically (e.g., via AWS Secrets Manager rotation). | Limits the usefulness of any credentials harvested through exploitation. |
| **Audit & Governance** | • Schedule **IAM policy drift detection** (e.g., using AWS Config rule `iam-policy-no-statements-with-full-access`).<br>• Conduct quarterly **privilege‑escalation tabletop exercises**. | Guarantees continuous visibility and readiness. |

