## MITRE ATT&CK Mobile – Technique **T0872 – Exfiltration Over Web Services**

| **Aspect** | **Details** |
|------------|--------------|
| **Goal of the adversary** | Move data from a compromised mobile device (or a cloud‑backed mobile app) to an external location by abusing legitimate web‑service APIs (e.g., Google Drive, Dropbox, OneDrive, Slack, AWS S3, Azure Blob, etc.). |
| **Why it matters for cloud environments** | Modern mobile apps are often thin clients that read/write directly to cloud storage or SaaS APIs. If an attacker can obtain a valid access token or credential, they can use the same APIs to upload stolen data, bypassing traditional network‑perimeter detections because the traffic looks like normal API calls. |
| **Typical indicators** | <ul><li>Unexpected `PutObject`, `UploadFile`, `CreateFile` API calls from a user‑agent that normally only reads data.</li><li>Spike in egress volume from a single device or service principal.</li><li>New OAuth scopes or service‑account keys created without a documented business need.</li><li>VPC Flow Logs showing outbound HTTPS to cloud‑storage endpoints from a non‑web‑tier subnet.</li></ul> |
| **Relevant telemetry sources** | • **AWS CloudTrail** (or Azure Activity Log / GCP Cloud Audit Logs) – API calls, IAM changes, credential creation.<br>• **VPC Flow Logs / Azure NSG Flow Logs** – network‑level egress patterns.<br>• **GuardDuty / Azure Defender / GCP Security Command Center** – anomalous data‑exfil alerts.<br>• **Endpoint‑telemetry (Mobile Device Management – MDM)** – app‑install, token usage, clipboard reads.<br>• **DLP logs** – content‑matching policies triggered on upload. |

