## 2. Core Remediation Principles (Secure‑by‑Design)

| Principle | How it defeats T0890 | Example Implementation |
|-----------|----------------------|------------------------|
| **Least Privilege IAM** | Reduces the “damage‑budget” an attacker can claim after exploitation. | Use scoped IAM policies that allow only the exact actions/resources needed. |
| **Zero‑Trust Trust Relationships** | Prevents any principal from blindly assuming a high‑privilege role. | Explicitly enumerate trusted principals; avoid `"Principal": "*"` in trust policies. |
| **Metadata Service Hardening** | Stops a compromised workload from silently pulling privileged tokens. | Enforce IMDSv2 (session‑token) and block IMDSv1 on all instances. |
| **Immutable, Signed Infrastructure as Code (IaC)** | Guarantees that policy changes are reviewed and auditable. | Store CDK/TF code in a signed Git repo; enforce PR approvals. |
| **Continuous Credential Hygiene** | Rotates secrets before they can be abused for long periods. | Enable automated secret rotation for IAM access keys, service‑principal passwords, and GCP service‑account keys. |
| **Defense‑in‑Depth Logging & Alerting** | Provides early detection of abnormal privilege‑escalation attempts. | Enable CloudTrail (AWS), Activity Log (Azure), Cloud Audit Logs (GCP) + GuardDuty/Defender/Chronicle. |
| **Patch Management & Runtime Hardening** | Removes the local exploit surface that attackers need to “break out”. | Use managed node groups with auto‑patching; run containers from minimal, scanned images. |

